---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import CaseStudy from "../../components/CaseStudy.astro";
---
<Layout
  title="Digital wallet, pre-launch behavioural research — Anmol Bhargava"
  description="Pre-launch research on a Saudi Arabia digital wallet. Re-prioritised launch readiness by adoption risk, not interface severity, and surfaced trust gaps the product team's assumptions had missed."
>
  <CaseStudy
    slug="digital-wallet"
    tldr={[
      { k: "Sector", v: "FinTech, digital wallet, Saudi Arabia" },
      { k: "Scope", v: "Activation, transfers, payments, post-transaction confirmation" },
      { k: "Method", v: "Moderated usability, journey-based friction mapping, behavioural prioritisation" },
      { k: "Lenses", v: "Entry trust, transaction trust, feedback trust" },
    ]}
    strategicShift='"Does it work?" → "Where does certainty collapse?"'
    problem={[
      "The product was feature-complete and approaching launch. One risk remained unresolved: whether users would feel confident enough to activate, transact, and return.",
      "In fintech, usability does more than capture preference. The interface has to earn enough trust for someone to move real money through it. Hesitation at sign-up, first transaction, or post-transfer confirmation compounds into abandonment quickly.",
      "The product team had strong assumptions about feature value. What was missing was a behavioural read on where certainty collapses under financial stakes.",
    ]}
    reframe={{
      label: "The reframe",
      intro:
        "Rather than treat the wallet as a single experience to evaluate, we decomposed it into three behavioural systems, each a distinct layer of trust users build sequentially.",
      layers: [
        { label: "Layer 01, Entry trust", body: "Do I feel safe signing up?" },
        { label: "Layer 02, Transaction trust", body: "Do I feel in control sending money?" },
        { label: "Layer 03, Feedback trust", body: "Do I know what happened?" },
      ],
    }}
    findings={[
      {
        lead: "KYC felt intrusive",
        body: "Multi-layer authentication came across as redundant friction. The protective intent behind it never quite registered for users. Effort was high while reassurance stayed thin.",
      },
      {
        lead: "Key actions were visually buried",
        body: "Under cognitive load, users scanned for action affordances and missed them. Time to first transaction stretched without a structural reason.",
      },
      {
        lead: "Feedback gaps eroded transaction trust silently",
        body: "Users often couldn't confirm whether money had arrived. The uncertainty surfaced later as repeat balance checks, well after the moment had passed.",
      },
      {
        lead: "Mental model failures concentrated at the start",
        body: "Users couldn't form a clean model of multi-layer auth on first encounter. The product had explained itself, but in the wrong order for how users were taking it in.",
      },
    ]}
    changed={[
      "Trust signalling brought forward into the first activation screens",
      "Security steps reframed from redundant friction to visible protection",
      "Homepage hierarchy restructured to match scanning behaviour under cognitive load",
      "Feedback loops scaffolded across transaction completion and confirmation",
    ]}
    takeaway="Research on high-trust products has to do more than validate the interface. The work is to find where certainty collapses, and make that actionable before the cost of discovery shifts from a research session to lost users at scale."
  />
</Layout>
